<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Jones, John. Letter to Judge Adam Mabane, 1787, with a copy of Jones's testimony 1783. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0003</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">That, <span class="DelHand-author">he began to read it, but that he was s<span class="Gap">[&#8230;]</span> and</span><span class="AddHand-author"> he was prevented being heard or</span> <span class="AddHand-author">reading the said paper of defence </span>prevented by M<sup>r</sup> Judge Mabane, <span class="AddHand-author">for</span> <span class="AddHand-author"><span class="AddHand-editors">[he]</span></span> <span class="AddHand-author">was overruled when he prayed to be heard.</span></p>
<p>That, he expostulated with the said Judge upon the Cruelty and Injustice of forbidding; absolutely forbidding him to plead his Clients Cause.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">That, M<sup>r</sup> Williams did also importune the said Judge to allow the Defendants objections against this motion to be read;</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">That M<sup>r</sup> Cochrane finding the entreaties of both these Lawyers unavailing, did address himself to M<sup>r</sup> Judge Mabane and say &#8220;It is in vain to look for Justice in this Court when the first Judge thereof brings Judgements in his Pocket ready <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Cut &amp; dry</span>.&#8221;</p>
<p class="positiveIndent">The answer which you have made to this, as contained in your Comments <span class="DelHand-author">decla<span class="AddHand-editors">[res]</span></span>.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="text-decoration:underline;">Declares That it appears by the Records,</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">That, On the 7th June 1783, the Solicitor M<sup>r</sup> Williams made a motion grounded <span style="text-decoration:underline;">on facts of a very serious and important Nature</span>, which the Court ordered to be communicated by M<sup>r</sup> Williams to M<sup>r</sup> Panet and <span style="text-decoration:underline;">that the same should be considered of by the Court.</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">That on the 11th June M<sup>r</sup> Williams moved for Judgement on his motion of the 7th June.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">That M<sup>r</sup> Panet <span style="text-decoration:underline;">read and filed</span> his written answer, <span style="text-decoration:underline;">upon which</span> the Court made the Entry or Interlocutory Order of that date (the 11th), not complying altogether with the Motion of M<sup>r</sup> Williams but providing a remedy</p>

